<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/945c3fa60f2dd28f7c929ada30ddb374> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Vogelboemerang\r\nDeze heel aparte boemerang met een sleuf, uitgesneden in de vorm van een vogel, komt waarschijnlijk uit zuidoostelijk Australië. Beide zijden van het hoofd zijn versierd met fijn gegrifte motieven die een ‘dansende’ figuur met een boemerang in de hand tonen en de kenmerkende emoe laten zien. Verder heeft het oppervlak fijn ingekraste stroken. Dergelijke versieringen komen vaak voor op speerwerpers uit zuidoostelijk Australië. Hoewel het aantal figuratieve tekeningen toenam in de contactperiode tussen 1840 en 1880, zijn de motieven toch kenmerkend voor de tijd vóór de Europese invloed. De bek van de vogel is duidelijk ingetekend met aan beide zijden een uitgesneden ‘neusgat’, een uiterst ongewoon element.\r\n\r\nMultifunctioneel\r\nDe Aborigines uit Zuidoost-Australië gebruikten twee boemerangtypes: het terugkerende en het niet-terugkerende model. Boemerangs konden gebruikt worden als messen, hamers, knotsen, graafstokken, om vuur te maken door wrijving, als percussie-instrument, maar natuurlijk ook voor de jacht en als wapen. Gezien de vorm kon dit exemplaar waarschijnlijk terugkeren, maar het vertoont toch een aantal aparte kenmerken zoals een uitlopende punt aan de ene kant en een bekvorm aan de andere. Terugkerende boemerangs beantwoorden aan verschillende fysische wetten: Bernoulli’s principe van verschillende luchtdruk, gyroscopische stabiliteit en voortgang alsook Newtons wet van beweging. \r\n\r\nOmzwervingen: van Australië via Sakhalin naar Nederland\r\nDeze boemerang heeft een buitengewone verzamelgeschiedenis. Hij werd omstreeks 1860 verzameld door de handelaar Friedrich August Lühdorf en maakte deel uit van een collectie uit de regio van de Amur-rivier in Siberië aangrenzend aan de zee van Okhotsk. Uit Lühdorfs briefwisseling toen hij zijn collectie in 1882 aan het museum overmaakte, blijkt dat hij de boemerang – die toen al gebroken was – op het eiland Sakhalin geruild had met een Ainu-man voor een zak rijst. Waarschijnlijk heeft deze boemerang zuidelijk Australië verlaten via de haven van Encounter Bay, ten zuiden van Adelaide of van Portland in westelijk Victoria. Deze belangrijke walvisvaarthavens waren actief tijdens de jaren 1840 tot het begin van de 1860er jaren. Het was heel normaal voor een walvisvaarder om tijdens een jachtseizoen van zuidelijk Australië naar de noordelijke Pacific te varen. \r\n\r\nDe Droomtijd\r\nNet als de fameuze boemerang, is ook het concept van de Droomtijd onlosmakelijk verbonden met de Aboriginal cultuur. De Droomtijd verbindt het verleden, heden en de toekomst. Het verklaart hoe het landschap door mythische wezens tot stand is gekomen, maar het biedt ook richtlijnen en wetten die aangeven hoe vandaag gehandeld moet worden om de continuïteit in de toekomst te verzekeren. Er is een grote diversiteit aan Droomtijdverhalen waarin de terugkerende boemerang centraal staat. De verhalen berichten over de magische vlucht van de boemerang, maar ook over hoe een object uit het zicht verdwijnt en dan op mysterieuze wijze weer verschijnt.\r\n\r\nDe roep van de havik\r\nEr zijn geen andere boemerangs bekend met een dergelijke gleuf. Wel vermelden etnografische bronnen dat Aboriginal jagers uit het zuidoosten hun boemerangs van een fluitend geluid voorzagen om de klank na te bootsen van de havik. Wanneer de boemerang boven een groep eenden gegooid werd, zouden de eenden heel laag gaan vliegen langs een waterweg en verstrengeld geraken in een net die andere jagers gespannen hadden. \r\n\r\nA very rare example of a south-western Western Australian boomerang type. Further notes to be made on this (Philip Jones)\r\n\r\nBoomerangs serve numerous functions.  Boomerangs are used as a knife, a hammer or club, a digging tool, for making fire by friction, for musical accompaniment as a percussion instrument as well as their main function as a hunting or fighting weapon. It is important to note that most fighting and hunting boomerangs were non-returning.  They were thrown to hit their targets and not return. Boomerangs are also used in games and competitions.  Furthermore, they have ceremonial uses, serving as objects of social and religious significance.  They are also produced for commercial reasons and are popular trade items.\r\n\r\nFor at least two reasons, the boomerang 680-9 is one of the more unusual pieces in the RMV’s Australian collection.  \r\nThe provenance of the boomerang is extraordinary. It was acquired by the Museum during 1882 from its collector, Baron Friedrich August Lühdorf, as part of a larger collection relating to the Amur River region of eastern Siberia, adjoining the Sea of Okhotsk. In correspondence with the Museum (June 1882), Lühdorf specifically mentioned this boomerang, recalling that he had acquired it about 20 years earlier on the island of Sakhalin. He had, he stated, exchanged a bag of rice for it with an Ainu man (a fisherman, as I recall).  Lühdorf also indicated that the boomerang was broken when he acquired it.\r\nWhen I first encountered a record of the boomerang in the TMS system during 2009, I was rather doubtful of its Australian provenance, as it was difficult to imagine circumstances in which a German collector might have acquired an Australian boomerang on a Russian island from an Ainu fisherman. A subsequent visit to the Museum store removed all doubt though, for the boomerang is engraved with characteristic Aboriginal motifs. That said, the second remarkable characteristic of the boomerang is its appearance.\r\nIn its general outline, the boomerang can be said to resemble the returning boomerangs of south-eastern or south-western Australia, with two pronounced variations. The first is that the slightly flared shape of one wing-tip (unusual but not extraordinary in returning boomerangs) is accentuated to a marked degree on the other wing-tip, giving the boomerang the overall effect of a serpentine shape or the shape of a bird, with the extended wing-tip suggesting a head, and the other suggesting a tail. This ‘figurative’ form is almost without precedent in an Aboriginal boomerang.  Despite that figurative or sculptural form, though, it seems that the boomerang would be capable of flight, and would probably return.\r\nThe second extraordinary variation in the boomerang’s form is immediately evident: the boomerang’s mid-section has a missing segment – a 270mm x 15 mm ‘slot’. That this ‘slot’ was incorporated in the boomerang from its first manufacture is evident from the fact that the delicate surface carvings or engravings which cover the surface extend to and from the slot to the edges of the boomerang. In other words, these carvings were not placed on the boomerang before the slot appeared. \r\nIt is the actual content, or subject, of these light surface carvings which confirm that the boomerang is, beyond doubt, Australian. Each side of the boomerang’s ‘head’ is decorated with finely scratched designs depicting a ‘dancing’ figure of a man holding boomerangs in each hand (6-8 mm long) and the characteristic figure of an emu. Otherwise, the boomerang’s surface is engraved with several thin bands of cross-hatching which are symmetrically applied, particularly in the boomerang’s mid-section. The engraved designs, both in their subject and execution, can be regarded as characteristic of those found on spearthrowers (in particular) of south-eastern Australia. While figurative designs seem to have increased in number during the ‘contact’ period in that area, i.e. from the 1840s and 1850s to the 1880s, it is fair to say that these particular designs are quite characteristic of the period before European influence. \r\nA further feature of the surface carving, which has been executed in cross-hatching with a very fine instrument, such as an animal tooth (or even a piece of glass or metal, perhaps), is that each side of the boomerang’s ‘head’ also bears the apparent design of a bird’s beak and above it, a ‘nostril’. This design could also be interpreted as a snake’s mouth and its nostril. I can send my own sketch of this feature, in a separate email. I have not seen any similar feature on another boomerang  If it had appeared just once, on one side of the boomerang, I would have discounted it, but the feature is reproduced on both sides of the boomerang’s bird-like head.\r\nIn the absence of any further clues as to the boomerang’s provenance, and with no ready explanation as to how it could have been collected by Lühdorf during the late 1850s or early 1860s on a Russian island in the Sea of Okhotsk, I have the following proposition. At first I was inclined to the view that the boomerang may have originated in the area of south-western Western Australia, for two reasons. First, the flared wing-tip of the ‘tail’ (leaving aside the very atypical head) seemed to suggest the returning boomerangs of south-western Western Australia, which have this characteristic. Second, carved message sticks from further north in Western Australia (Roebourne area) do bear similar designs of fine cross-hatching, and it occurred to me that these elements may have combined to produce a boomerang which may have been traded to American whalers at Albany in south-western Australia, and subsequently brought north to the Sea of Okhotsk by a whaling ship.\r\nMy current thinking though, is that the figurative designs on the boomerang, as well as the light cross-hatched bands, and the shape of the boomerang itself, are consistent with a provenance relating to south-eastern Australia. The returning boomerang was used in a wide area of south-eastern Australia, and in at least two localities visited by whalers who might subsequently have sailed to the Sea of Okhotsck and to Sakhalin. The Encounter Bay whale fishery, south of Adelaide, operated during the 1840s, and the Portland fishery in western Victoria spanned the same period and continued into the 1850s. Both are possible sources for this boomerang. A whaling ship might range from Australian waters to the northern Pacific during the course of a single season. \r\nIt is known that Aboriginal men sometimes accompanied and worked for these whaling ships. It is intriguing to think that one of these men might have taken a returning boomerang with him, to impress the crew and people of other lands with his skill in making it return. Perhaps, seeing the scrimshaw work of other crewmen on the whaling ships, he was inspired to carve this boomerang into a figurative shape, and to embellish it with fine designs, including figures of men and animals. Perhaps he demonstrated the boomerang to an astonished Ainu fisherman at Sakhalin, who retained the boomerang until Friedrich August Lühdorf arrived there. It is worth noting that Lühdorf first visited the Amur region, based at Nikolaevsk, as an agent of the Godeffroy shipping company. He would therefore have been familiar with the Godeffroy Museum in Hamburg and attuned to the ethnographic potential of his expeditions to Japan, Siberia and places in between. By the early 1860s Lühdorf had become the German consul to the Amur trading zone, and had been one of the first westerners to take advantage of the new trading relationship with Japan brought about by the American, Commodore Perry. \r\nAs for the slot in the boomerang, this remains something of a mystery, although it is known from the ethnographic record that Aboriginal hunters of south-eastern (and probably south-western) Australia aimed to impart a whistling sound to their returning boomerangs, so that they would mimic the sound of a hawk when thrown above a flock of ducks. This would cause the ducks to fly low along a watercourse, tangling themselves in a net strung across it by other hunters. To my knowledge there are no other boomerangs in museum collections with this ‘slot’, but it would certainly be worth making a replica boomerang and testing it, to see whether it produces that whistling sound. \r\nFinally, I’d stress again the importance of taking a small wood sample from this boomerang. It should enable us to identify the particular tree species, and therefore to finally pin down the provenance of this fascinating object.\r\n\r\nPostscript: If I was to publish this article, in an expanded form perhaps, with illustrations, I would certainly acknowledge the help received from Mette and others at the Museum, with translation of the Lühdorf letters, etc.\r\n  \r\nPhilip Jones, 11 June 2012" .
